00:36:06.480 --> 00:36:08.220
So let's talk about
Play Games and what

00:36:08.220 --> 00:36:11.160
it means to build a
sense of belonging.

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:13.680
We launched this feature
that we call Quests.

00:36:13.680 --> 00:36:17.600
And it's acknowledging that many
highly successful games know

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:20.800
how to build and engage a
vibrant community of players.

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:23.700
And sometimes this takes the
form of a weekend challenge

00:36:23.700 --> 00:36:25.260
to find rare objects.

00:36:25.260 --> 00:36:27.370
Or in the case of
Pixelberry, they'll

00:36:27.370 --> 00:36:29.390
progress their
story through a set

00:36:29.390 --> 00:36:31.980
of in-game objectives
for a period of time.

00:36:31.980 --> 00:36:33.800
But running these timed
events is actually

00:36:33.800 --> 00:36:35.360
tricky for developers.

00:36:35.360 --> 00:36:37.530
And we thought our game
services would help.

00:36:37.530 --> 00:36:39.900
So Quests is a set
of APIs that allow

00:36:39.900 --> 00:36:42.600
you to run these time-based
events for your players

00:36:42.600 --> 00:36:45.740
and reward them without
needing to update your game.

00:36:45.740 --> 00:36:51.730
To do this, developers send us
in-game activity data whenever

00:36:51.730 --> 00:36:54.200
a player successfully
accomplishes something

00:36:54.200 --> 00:36:58.690
in the game, like completing
a level, killing an alien,

00:36:58.690 --> 00:37:01.160
saving a rare black sheep.

00:37:01.160 --> 00:37:03.900
This tells Quests what's
going on in the game.

00:37:03.900 --> 00:37:05.880
And developers can
use that game activity

00:37:05.880 --> 00:37:08.290
to create these new quests
and run these quests

00:37:08.290 --> 00:37:12.549
on a regular basis as
players achieve the goals.

00:37:12.549 --> 00:37:14.090
We think it's going
to be a fantastic

00:37:14.090 --> 00:37:16.300
tool for re-engagement
and retention.

00:37:16.300 --> 00:37:17.980
And I'll take you
through a little bit,

00:37:17.980 --> 00:37:20.130
very quickly, how it works.

00:37:20.130 --> 00:37:23.500
First, we start by using our
events API and defining events

00:37:23.500 --> 00:37:27.140
of in-game activities inside
of the Play Developer Console.

00:37:27.140 --> 00:37:28.940
So let's say it's a
pirate game, and it's

00:37:28.940 --> 00:37:31.770
the number of treasures
you've discovered in the game.

00:37:31.770 --> 00:37:34.970
You integrate the events in your
game and our Quests listener.

00:37:34.970 --> 00:37:36.940
And signed-in
players start sending

00:37:36.940 --> 00:37:39.620
signals of that
in-game activity.

00:37:39.620 --> 00:37:41.220
You can then use the
Developer Console

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:43.880
to monitor which
activities are being used.

00:37:43.880 --> 00:37:47.370
So let's pretend for a
moment that this treasure

00:37:47.370 --> 00:37:51.000
mechanic in my pirate game
is actually pretty popular

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:53.750
and that everybody loves
discovering hidden treasure.

00:37:53.750 --> 00:37:55.870
So I can go into the
Play Developer Console,

00:37:55.870 --> 00:37:57.110
and I can define a quest.

00:37:57.110 --> 00:37:58.770
I can use treasures,
the events that

00:37:58.770 --> 00:38:01.431
are being sent to me, as
the criteria for completing

00:38:01.431 --> 00:38:01.930
the quest.

00:38:01.930 --> 00:38:07.400
So for example, I can create a
find 50 treasures this weekend

00:38:07.400 --> 00:38:11.170
game super secret awesome
reward for your trouble.

00:38:11.170 --> 00:38:13.140
And I publish it.

00:38:13.140 --> 00:38:16.425
And as players go through
that and accept the quest

00:38:16.425 --> 00:38:19.540
and go through that
activity in your game,

00:38:19.540 --> 00:38:22.670
we automatically
aggregate the criteria

00:38:22.670 --> 00:38:27.000
that you defined in your quest
and describe to your game

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.840
when somebody has accomplished
the goal, or whether time's up

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:30.960
and they have it.

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:32.840
And we'll send a
unique reward code,

00:38:32.840 --> 00:38:36.060
so you can design your game to
reward those users every time

00:38:36.060 --> 00:38:37.560
they complete a quest.

00:38:37.560 --> 00:38:40.500
The beauty of this design is
you can continue to run Quests

00:38:40.500 --> 00:38:42.730
without updating your
game because it's entirely

00:38:42.730 --> 00:38:44.230
data driven.

00:38:44.230 --> 00:38:47.130
And we're really excited
to see what's going on here

00:38:47.130 --> 00:38:49.580
and what you will
do with Quests when

00:38:49.580 --> 00:38:51.560
it launches in a couple weeks.

00:38:51.560 --> 00:38:54.390
And those experiences for Quests
will show up in the Play Games

00:38:54.390 --> 00:38:57.070
App by showing
